Iterate over each element of a collection

Python makes this look like almost natural language:for [each] value in [the] list

for N in [2, 3, 5, 7]:
    print(N, end=' ') # print all on same line



for N in range(5):
    print(N, end=' ')



for N in range(1, 10, 2):
    print(N, end=' ')

# Multiplication table till 4
for i in range(1, 5):
    for j in range(1, 5):
        print(f'{i} times {j} is {i*j}')
    print() # white line



Note: every further nested loop increases the computation time by a factor of N, where N =  number of iterations steps. It is good practice to optimize your code in order to avoid unnecessary loops i.e. by using vectorization. Specifically, this means using functions in third party libraries that operate on vectors.

There may be times when you want to interrupt the predefined flow of a loop:

students_grades = {"Freddy": 1.3, "Laura": 1.0, "Bobby": 5.0, "Betty": 2.3}
everyone_passed = True

for stud in students_grades:
    if students_grades[stud] > 4.0:
        everyone_passed = False
        break # terminate the for-loop and proceed to the next code block after the loop

if everyone_passed:
    print("Good job.")
else:
    print("Someone didn't pass")



students_grades = {"Freddy": 1.3, "Laura": 1.0, "Bobby": 5.0, "Betty": 2.3}

for stud in students_grades:
    if students_grades[stud] > 4.0:
        continue # interrupts the current iteration and proceeds to the next one

    print(f"Good job, {stud}")

Applies a function to a collection

def power_of(x, y=2):
    return x**y

for n in map(power_of, range(5)):
    print(n)



def power_of(x, y=2):
    return x**y

for n in map(power_of, range(5), [3]*5):
    print(n)

Unordered collections of unique items

Support set operations

Defined by {1, 2, 3}

primes = {2, 3, 5, 7}
odds = {1, 3, 5, 7, 9}

items appearing in either set

primes = {2, 3, 5, 7}
odds = {1, 3, 5, 7, 9}
primes | odds      # with an operator
primes.union(odds) # equivalently with a method

items appearing in both sets

primes = {2, 3, 5, 7}
odds = {1, 3, 5, 7, 9}
primes & odds             # with an operator
primes.intersection(odds) # equivalently with a method

items appearing in one but not other set

primes = {2, 3, 5, 7}
odds = {1, 3, 5, 7, 9}
primes - odds           # with an operator
primes.difference(odds) # equivalently with a method

items appearing in only one set

primes = {2, 3, 5, 7}
odds = {1, 3, 5, 7, 9}
primes ^ odds                     # with an operator
primes.symmetric_difference(odds) # equivalently with a method

